\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 The Effect of a Mediterranean Diet on Glycemic Control in Patients With Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus: A Randomized Controlled Study\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Background:
\f0\b0  Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) is a major global health concern associated with significant morbidity and mortality. Dietary modification plays a critical role in glycemic control and prevention of complications. The Mediterranean diet has been associated with improved metabolic outcomes, but evidence from randomized controlled studies remains limited.\

\f1\b Objective:
\f0\b0  To evaluate the effects of a Mediterranean diet on glycemic control, lipid profile, and body mass index (BMI) in patients with T2DM.\

\f1\b Methods:
\f0\b0  A 24-week randomized controlled trial was conducted involving 120 adults diagnosed with T2DM. Participants were randomly assigned to either a Mediterranean diet intervention group or a standard diabetic diet control group. Primary outcomes included changes in glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c). Secondary outcomes included fasting plasma glucose, lipid profile, BMI, and blood pressure.\

\f1\b Results:
\f0\b0  Participants in the Mediterranean diet group demonstrated a statistically significant reduction in HbA1c levels compared to the control group (\uc0\u8722 1.2% vs. \u8722 0.5%, p < 0.001). Significant improvements were also observed in LDL cholesterol, triglycerides, and BMI. No serious adverse events were reported.\

\f1\b Conclusion:
\f0\b0  The Mediterranean diet significantly improves glycemic control and cardiovascular risk factors in patients with T2DM. These findings support the incorporation of Mediterranean dietary patterns into diabetes management guidelines.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
