\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Methods\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Study Design\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This study was a single-center, randomized, controlled, parallel-group trial conducted over 24 weeks. Ethical approval was obtained from the institutional review board, and all participants provided written informed consent prior to enrollment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Participants\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 A total of 120 adults aged 40\'9670 years with a diagnosis of T2DM for at least one year were recruited from outpatient endocrinology clinics. Inclusion criteria included HbA1c levels between 7.0% and 10.0% and stable antidiabetic medication for at least three months. Exclusion criteria included insulin therapy, advanced renal or hepatic disease, active malignancy, or adherence to a Mediterranean diet prior to enrollment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Randomization and Intervention\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Participants were randomly assigned in a 1:1 ratio to either the Mediterranean diet group or the control group using a computer-generated randomization sequence.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Mediterranean Diet Group:
\f0\b0  Participants received individualized nutritional counseling and were instructed to follow a Mediterranean dietary pattern emphasizing olive oil as the primary fat source, increased intake of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, legumes, nuts, and fish, with limited red meat and processed foods.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Control Group:
\f0\b0  Participants followed a standard diabetic diet based on national dietary guidelines, focusing on calorie restriction, reduced fat intake, and carbohydrate control.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Both groups received monthly follow-up visits with a dietitian.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Outcome Measures\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The primary outcome was change in HbA1c from baseline to week 24. Secondary outcomes included fasting plasma glucose, lipid profile (total cholesterol, LDL, HDL, triglycerides), BMI, and blood pressure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Statistical Analysis\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Data were analyzed using intention-to-treat principles. Continuous variables were expressed as mean \'b1 standard deviation. Between-group comparisons were performed using independent t-tests, while within-group changes were assessed using paired t-tests. A p-value < 0.05 was considered statistically significant.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
