\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Discussion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This randomized controlled study demonstrates that adherence to a Mediterranean diet significantly improves glycemic control and metabolic parameters in patients with T2DM. The observed reduction in HbA1c is clinically meaningful and comparable to the effect of some pharmacological agents.\
Several mechanisms may explain these findings. The high content of monounsaturated fats, dietary fiber, and antioxidants in the Mediterranean diet may enhance insulin sensitivity and reduce inflammation. Additionally, the emphasis on whole foods and low glycemic index carbohydrates likely contributes to improved postprandial glucose control.\
The improvements in lipid profile observed in this study align with previous research highlighting the cardiovascular benefits of the Mediterranean diet. Given the elevated cardiovascular risk associated with T2DM, these findings are particularly relevant.\
This study has limitations, including its single-center design and reliance on self-reported dietary adherence. Longer follow-up periods are needed to assess sustainability and long-term outcomes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Conclusion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Mediterranean diet is an effective and safe dietary intervention for improving glycemic control and reducing cardiovascular risk factors in patients with T2DM. Healthcare providers should consider recommending this dietary pattern as part of comprehensive diabetes management.\
